    #video-equipment-section-1
      %div
        %h2 Laptop
        %p
          The setup allows for multiple screens to be connected and switched easily but is limited to devices with HDMI.
          Digital outputs like display port can also be supported with
          %a{ href: "http://amzn.to/1UPMJby", target: "_blank" } adapters.
        %p You can follow the dotted lines to see how all the equipment is connected.
    #video-equipment-section-2
      %div
        %h2 HDMI Switch
        %p
          The switch makes the handover to speakers seamless by pressing one button and does not interrupt video recording further down the line. We use the
          %a{ href: "http://amzn.to/1UPN7Hd", target: "_blank" } Betron 3 Port HDMI Switch.
    #video-equipment-section-3
      %div
        %h2 HDMI Splitter
        %p
          This is the secret sauce of having a good setup. Sometimes we go out to two screens making the splitter necessary without forcing the speaker to go into mirrored mode.
        %p
          The splitter however serves an additional purpose in that it strips DRM meaning your captures won't fail in the middle of the talk. We use
          %a{ href: "http://amzn.to/1Mm8e10", target: "_blank" } this one
          from Portta.
    #video-equipment-section-4
      %div
        %h2 Capture Device & Mic
        %p
          Software capture is hard to organise, inconsistent and can slow down a machine that is already having a hard time running two screens.
        %p
          Hooking up a capture device also means you can get a single recording of the whole night making editing much easier.
        %p
          The
          %a{ href: "http://amzn.to/1S2Ee9u", target: "_blank" }
          mic
          simply captures the speaker without much background noise
    #video-equipment-section-5
      %div
        %h2 Screen
        %p
          You often don't have the control about where the content is displayed but if you do I'd highly recommend a TV for audiences up to 100 people and a high lumens projector for anything larger.
        %p
          Most presenters will write there slides in 16:9 (1920 x 1080) these days so keep this in consideration and let your speakers know your setup early.
    #video-equipment-section-6
      %div
        %h2 Camcorder
        %p You could just record the screen but body language says so much. I'd recommend investing in a low to mid range camcorder to capture your talks speakers.
        %p The video quality should be good enough that it isn't distracting, battery life and quality of the microphone if far more important in my experience.
        %p
          We use a
          %a{ href: "http://amzn.to/1Mm8XPK", target: "_blank" } Sony HDRPJ810
          that I picked up on an Amazon lightning deal for just £399. It has built in memory but we use a
          %a{ href: "http://amzn.to/1Mm9m4I", target: "_blank" } high speed SD card
          so I don't have the take the camera with me when I'm editing.


    #video-equipment-section-7
      %div
        %h2 Syncing
        %p
          Great now you've got the content in a few places, you might have noticed that the audio has been captured in two places this is for two reasons.
        %p 1. Synchronisation of the camcorder and capture device can be done automagicly with the audio.
        %p 2. The capture device mic is great for picking up the speaker without background noise, but the camera mic is great capturing the audio during Q&A.
    #video-equipment-section-8
      %div
        %h2 Final Cut Pro X
        %p
          Editing is made super easy with
          %a{ href: "https://itunes.apple.com/gb/app/final-cut-pro/id424389933?mt=12" } Final Cut Pro X.
          Just make a multi-cam clip from your two sources, drop it into a project, open the multi-cam view and simply click the source you want shown whist watching back in real-time.
        %p Pro tip: If your tight for time you can do this at 2x speed using the timewarp feature.
        %p
          We use a
          %a{ href: "http://amzn.to/1Mm9SzL", target: "_blank" } 2TB external HDD
          since most of these projects reach at least 20GB.

